## Structure 2: The chain (mediation)

When `X` affects `Y` only through a mediator `M`, the total causal effect is identified *without* adjusting for `M`.
In fact, conditioning on `M` would block the causal path and bias the total effect estimate.

```{dot}
//| label: fig-chain-dag
//| fig-cap: "Chain DAG: X affects Y only through M. Do not adjust for M when estimating the total effect."
//| fig-width: 3
digraph {
  rankdir=LR
  X -> M
  M -> Y
}
```

::: {#793b94b4 .cell execution_count=5}
``` {.python .cell-code}
X = rng.normal(size=n)
M = 0.6 * X + rng.normal(scale=0.5, size=n)
Y = 0.5 * M + rng.normal(scale=0.5, size=n)

df_chain = pd.DataFrame({"X": X, "M": M, "Y": Y})

chain_model = pathmc.model(
    """
    M ~ X
    Y ~ M
    """,
    data=df_chain,
)
chain_model.equations()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown execution_count=5}
$$
\begin{aligned}
\beta_{M} &\sim \text{Normal}(mu=0,\, sigma=10) \\
\sigma_{M} &\sim \text{HalfNormal}(sigma=1) \\
\beta_{Y} &\sim \text{Normal}(mu=0,\, sigma=10) \\
\sigma_{Y} &\sim \text{HalfNormal}(sigma=1)
\\[6pt]
\mu_{M} &= \beta_{0,\,M} + \mathrm{X} \\
\mathrm{M} &\sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{M},\, \sigma_{M}) \\
\mu_{Y} &= \beta_{0,\,Y} + \mathrm{M} \\
\mathrm{Y} &\sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{Y},\, \sigma_{Y})
\end{aligned}
$$
:::
:::


::: {#0d8d0920 .cell execution_count=6}
``` {.python .cell-code}
print(f"Identifiable?    {chain_model.is_identifiable('X', 'Y')}")
print(f"Adjustment sets: {chain_model.adjustment_sets('X', 'Y')}")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Identifiable?    True
Adjustment sets: [set()]
```
:::
:::


The empty set is valid — no adjustment needed.
Notice that `M` does not appear in any adjustment set: it is a descendant of `X` and therefore excluded from backdoor adjustment.

::: {#624852c8 .cell execution_count=7}
``` {.python .cell-code}
chain_model.fit(draws=500, tune=500, chains=2, random_seed=42)

ate = chain_model.ate("Y", "X")
ate
```

